xkRNpU ] is one of them. It=E2=80=99s the best way to understand a company =
or industry like the insiders do, in their own words.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m in the middle of writing a Deep Dive on one of the most complex=
 companies I=E2=80=99ve written about to date, and I spent two hours on Teg=
us [ https://substack.com/redirect/d76726f4-09f7-4531-85c6-c62212ce5b28?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] Wednesd=
ay reading interviews with their customers. It would have been longer, but =
Tegus now summarizes and bullets each transcript right at the top of each o=
ne.=C2=A0
Tegus [ https://substack.com/redirect/d76726f4-09f7-4531-85c6-c62212ce5b28?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is ful=
l of transcripts of conversations with insiders and executives in any indus=
try you can think of. It boasts 75% of the world=E2=80=99s private market t=
ranscripts. If you want to learn about energy, space, biotech, name it, fro=
m the people who actually work and buy in those markets, Tegus [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/d76726f4-09f7-4531-85c6-c62212ce5b28?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is the spot.=C2=A0
With Tegus [ https://substack.com/redirect/d76726f4-09f7-4531-85c6-c62212ce=
5b28?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =
you gain access to the pulse of the private markets =E2=80=93 with perspect=
ives and detailed financials you won=E2=80=99t find anywhere else. There=E2=
=80=99s a reason the world=E2=80=99s best private market investors use Tegu=
s, and as a smart, curious Not Boring reader, you can get access to the Teg=
us platform today:
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 111th Weekly Dose of Optimism. Coming =
into the end of this week, I didn=E2=80=99t have a plan for what I was goin=
g to write about =E2=80=94 I of course had concepts of a plan =E2=80=94 but=
 no real plan. But then, as always, we humans pulled through. Private space=
walks, AI models of scientific research, lithium pioneers, and much, much m=
ore.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
(1) SpaceX employee, tech billionaire conduct first spacewalk in Polaris mi=
ssion [ https://substack.com/redirect/ed00ee09-1c2f-49bf-bdd5-0a300774c294?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Joey Roulette [ https://substack.com/redirect/f82e387d-c939-4ddd-84d0-bdc51=
6d19ffb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] and Gerry Doyle [ https://substack.com/redirect/d5b5e93e-563b-4ed0-9e9f-9=
1b6d152e1da?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] for Reuters
Two astronauts from a SpaceX capsule in Earth's orbit carried out the world=
's first private spacewalk on Thursday, tethered to the Crew Dragon spacecr=
aft in the vacuum of space while two others watched from inside, hundreds o=
f miles from Earth.
Two nights ago, SpaceX pulled off the first private spacewalk in history an=
d took humans farther out in space than we=E2=80=99ve gone in over five dec=
ades. Jared Isaacman, the billionaire founder of Shift4 payments (and star =
of this Netflix show) and SpaceX engineer, Sarah Gillis, were the two priva=
te astronauts aboard the mission.
The SpaceX Polaris missions are a series of private spaceflight missions ai=
med at advancing human spaceflight capabilities and conducting scientific r=
esearch. Polaris is a collaboration between SpaceX and Isaacman=E2=80=A6and=
 I guess fronting some cash got Isaacman the exclusive ticket to be the fir=
st civilian to walk in space ever.
The Polaris missions are comprised of three missions: Polaris Dawn (the afo=
rementioned mission), Mission II (an extension of Dawn), and Mission III (t=
he first human spaceflight of SpaceX=E2=80=99s Starship vehicle). For Space=
X and Isaacman, Dawn was one not-so small step for Polaris and one giant le=
ap for mankind.=20
(2) The Lone Star Lithium Boom [ https://substack.com/redirect/078d40b5-6c6=
e-4f5c-8367-8765a5078b44?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Russell Gold for Texas Monthly
The brine containing the most lithium he=E2=80=99s found in North America, =
rivaling the best in the world, lies beneath a one-hundred-mile swath of no=
rtheast Texas and southern Arkansas. It=E2=80=99s a mostly rural area of so=
aring pines and muddy bayous. Burba=E2=80=99s home, where he and Carol move=
d in 2021 to be nearer her aging parents, sits smack in the middle of it.
The race is on to turn this area=E2=80=94home to a subterranean limestone f=
ormation known as the Smackover [ https://substack.com/redirect/5a80ebba-32=
d8-44ba-8f6a-66d1e28f3aca?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], once a productive oil field=E2=80=94into a globally si=
gnificant lithium producer.
We=E2=80=99re going to need a lot more lithium. Like hundreds of thousands =
of tons more lithium.
Thankfully, we have people like John Burba among us. Back in the 90s, the T=
exan chemist invented a method called Direct Lithium Extraction (DLE) that =
could revolutionize lithium mining, making it faster, cheaper, and more env=
ironmentally friendly. His technology uses a fiber-reinforced polymer cylin=
der filled with granules to extract lithium from brine in less than an hour=
, compared to the months or years required by traditional methods. Today, D=
LE is used in some parts of the world, but Burba is now bringing it to the =
U.S. in a potentially big way.
Burba's company recently launched the first commercial DLE lithium mine in =
the U.S., specifically in Texas and Arkansas. The two states sit atop the S=
mackover formation, a subterranean limestone reservoir rich in lithium-cont=
aining brine. This brine has relatively high concentrations of lithium, esp=
ecially in northeast Texas region, where levels rival some of the best depo=
sits worldwide.
If Burba is successful, it could significantly boost lithium production in =
the U.S., reducing reliance on foreign sources and supporting the rapid gro=
wth of the electric vehicle and renewable energy markets.
We need more John Burbas.
(3) Introducing Chai-1: Decoding the molecular interactions of life [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/15460543-e655-43ee-9c57-072240606b65?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From The Chai Discovery Team
We=E2=80=99re excited to release Chai-1, a new multi-modal foundation model=
 for molecular structure prediction that performs at the state-of-the-art a=
cross a variety of tasks relevant to drug discovery. Chai-1 enables unified=
 prediction of proteins, small molecules, DNA, RNA, covalent modifications,=
 and more.
Chai Discovery introduced Chai-1, an AI model for predicting the structures=
 and interactions of various molecules, including proteins and DNA, which i=
s crucial for drug discovery and biomedical research. Chai-1 offers improve=
d accuracy over existing models, like DeepMind=E2=80=99s AlphaFold models, =
and can predict molecular structures using single sequences, making it more=
 versatile and accessible.
The model is freely available for commercial use via a web interface, and i=
ts code is released for non-commercial purposes, aiming to foster collabora=
tion across research and industry.
Today, drug discovery is a extremely complex, multi-step process and the id=
ea that we can totally outsource it to AI is a little far flung. Zach Weinb=
erg, on the new podcast =E2=80=9CThis Won=E2=80=99t Last [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/94a90d0d-4681-4e53-8e0=
f-246e405f219a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]," offered a cooling perspectiv=
e on AI=E2=80=99s impact on drug discovery. But using models like Chai-1 (a=
nd the inevitable more advanced models that follow it from folks like Chai =
Discovery and AlphaFold), can carry a lot of the load and hopefully overtim=
e increase the velocity and volume of drug discoveries.
(4) Language Agents Achieve Superhuman Synthesis of Scientific Knowledge [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/e1fee5a7-88e2-4c63-8e27-d8f944b8cb7a?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From FutureHouse
Introducing PaperQA2, the first AI agent that conducts entire scientific li=
terature reviews on its own. PaperQA2 is also the first agent to beat PhD a=
nd Postdoc-level biology researchers on multiple literature research tasks,=
 as measured both by accuracy on objective benchmarks and assessments by hu=
man experts. We are publishing a paper and open-sourcing the code. This is =
the first example of AI agents exceeding human performance on a major porti=
on of scientific research, and will be a game-changer for the way humans in=
teract with the scientific literature.
Speaking of AI taking on a larger load of scientific research, the team at =
FutureHouse unveiled PaperQA2. We=E2=80=99ve covered how AI will impact sci=
entific research before, but PaperQA2 stands out for a number of reasons:
Automated Literature Reviews: It's the first AI agent capable of conducting=
 comprehensive scientific literature reviews independently.
Superhuman Performance: It outperform PhD students and postdoctoral researc=
hers in literature review tasks.
High-Accuracy RAG: The tool utilizes high-accuracy retrieval augmented gene=
ration (RAG) techniques, focusing specifically on scientific literature.
Versatile Input Handling: It=E2=80=99s multi-modal, meaning it can process =
information from various sources, including PDFs and text files (which can =
include raw HTML).
Claim Extraction and Verification: It can extract claims from papers and cr=
oss-reference them against the existing literature to identify potential co=
ntradictions.
PaperAQ2 (and subsequent models) could significantly streamline the scienti=
fic research process and help scientists navigate and synthesize the vast b=
ody of scientific research, leading to faster and more breakthroughs.
Man science is going to be crazy in a couple of years.
(5) Researchers Astonished: When Air in Daycares Was Purified, Children's I=
llnesses Significantly Decreased [ https://substack.com/redirect/657f632a-c=
6de-45b1-b515-5624734a4343?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Hanna Ter=C3=A4v=C3=A4 for YLE
Contrary to expectations, it was found that simply purifying the air in day=
cares reduced children's illnesses by as much as 18.2%. The age and gender =
of the children did not affect the number of infections.
I=E2=80=99m not a parent. But I=E2=80=99m around enough parents to know tha=
t a top 3 complaint during the first years of their children=E2=80=99s live=
s is that the kids are always sick and, as a result, the parents are always=
 sick. You don=E2=80=99t need to live in Park Slope to understand this.
Thankfully, a two-year study in Helsinki daycares found that purifying the =
air reduced children's illnesses by 18.2%. The findings primarily challenge=
 the belief that daycare illnesses mainly spread through droplets and conta=
ct. The study suggests a significant portion of infections are airborne, me=
aning that air purification systems could be an effective and cost-friendly=
 way of reducing daycare (and other public area) sickness.
Fewer kids getting sick at daycare is a win in its own right. But when you =
extrapolate out the true costs of a sick kid, the benefit is greater =E2=80=
=94 parents will get less sick and will need to take off less time from wor=
k to care for their children and themselves.
Then, the only issue will be, what will these new parents talk about all th=
e time? I guess we=E2=80=99ll always have sleep.=20
Bonuses
Packy here. After Dan sent me this draft, the hits just kept on coming, so =
I=E2=80=99m going to call them out ever so briefly.=20
First, Anduril announced [ https://substack.com/redirect/a5b2f7e3-cded-4180=
-a0e4-e7719bade82a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ] Barracuda-M =E2=80=94 =E2=80=9Cthe most producible cruise miss=
iles on the market=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 with this absolute banger of a video =
that I=E2=80=99ve been playing on repeat for the past 18 hours.=20
The company heard the message that America can=E2=80=99t produce mass at th=
e same scale as China, and it took that personally. Not only are Barracudas=
 designed to be produced faster and more cheaply, they=E2=80=99re able to w=
ork together on top of Anduril=E2=80=99s Lattice OS.=20
The irony is that the more weapons you=E2=80=99re able to produce, the fewe=
r you=E2=80=99ll actually have to use. Here=E2=80=99s to thousands of Barra=
cuda=E2=80=99s sitting on the shelf, just deterring.=20
Then, OpenAI released its new o1 model series [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/815fa0e5-55d9-4b7c-9057-6161f6c28df6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the long-awaited =F0=9F=8D=93, fka Q*, r=
umors of which first emerged back when Sam Altman was fired and re-hired. T=
his, some thought, is what Ilya saw.=20
The short explanation (read Noam Brown=E2=80=99s thread for more detail [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/815fa0e5-55d9-4b7c-9057-6161f6c28df6?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]) is that the o1=
 models are much, much better at reasoning than previous models because the=
y=E2=80=99re trained to pause and think before they respond. =E2=80=9CThe l=
onger it thinks, the better it does on reasoning tasks.=E2=80=9D Probably a=
 lesson in there for us humans=E2=80=A6=20
And finally, Bradley Tusk wrote a book called Vote With Your Phone [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/ba826e4b-26b6-4fca-b977-79d70a9a26af?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] about increasing you=
th voter turnout in the US by letting people vote with their phones, with a=
 detailed plan on how to do it without inviting a flood of fraud. It comes =
out Tuesday. Bradley knows a thing or two about the intersection of politic=
s and mobile. He=E2=80=99s the architect of my favorite startup campaign ev=
er: Uber=E2=80=99s DeBlasio Mode [ https://substack.com/redirect/d3bbbfba-a=
ab6-4ad6-bfed-a03bf78f9fd6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Worth a read.=20
OK, I think we=E2=80=99re done for now=E2=80=A6=20
Have a great weekend y=E2=80=99all.
Thanks to Tegus [ https://substack.com/redirect/d76726f4-09f7-4531-85c6-c62=
212ce5b28?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] for sponsoring! We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tuesday.
Thanks for reading,
Packy + Dan

